\doublespace\large{
\chapter{\\ORIGINS OF THE RETROTRANSPOSON ANTISENSE BIAS}
The non-random distribution of RTs can be used to facilitate studies into the variable effects that RTs impart on genes; effects that may be accompanied by phenotypic changes. The distribution of RTs is only useful in these studies, however, if it is due to forces acting on phenotypes (i.e.: selection) as opposed to non-phenotype associated mechanisms such as integration preferences. Studies attempting to determine the mechanistic underpinnings leading to changes in RT distribution over time have identified that selection plays a role in the genome-wide distribution of RTs (section \ref{sec:dist}), but it is unknown if the altered distribution observed within genes is also due to forces of selection.

Despite the knowledge that selection acts on RTs in general, there are two major questions that are yet to be resolved, i) is the altered distribution of RTs, specifically within genes, due to selection and ii) are the selective forces acting on RTs positive or negative (purifying). Although the first question (i) may seem like an minor detail to pursue, it is vital to future studies attempting to discern the phenotypic effects of RTs on genes. It is important because there are altered distributions of RTs within genes that, if they are due to selection, can be used to predict the phenotypic impact of future insertions. This knowledge would therefore inform future disease studies investigating the association between RTs and phenotype. If instead the altered distribution of RTs in genes is due to the non phenotype-dependent force of integration then these predictions would be unfounded, and perhaps misleading. Therefore, before further analyses on phenotypic associations with RTs distributions are analyzed, it must be determined whether RT integration is the force driving altered distribution of RTs within genes, or if forces associated with phenotype (i.e.: selection) are the driving force.

The RT antisense bias (AS bias) is a powerful example of altered distributions of RTs within genes that can be used to delineate between effects of selection versus integration. AS bias is the tendency of RTs to be present in the antisense (AS) orientation within genes more often than the sense (S) orientation. An interesting feature of AS bias is that it peaks near transcription start sites (TSS), as do the total number of RTs \cite{Medstrand2002}.

This recurring altered distribution of AS bias towards transcription start sites may indicate an mechanism of selection, however it may also indicate a preference for integration locations. An argument for the enrichment of  RTs  near the TSS is that there is increased open chromatin near the TSS and therefore increased accesibility to the L1 ORF2p endonuclease. However, if open chromatin was the reason for the increase in RTs then this preference should be replicated in both the sense and antisense orientations. Moreover, since L1 ORF2p endonucleases cleaves dsDNA \cite{Feng1996}, there should be no preference for integration due to single-strand accesibility. Also, it has been shown that L1 in the S orientation decrease expression of a coincident gene, however the same effect is not true of L1 in the AS orientation \cite{Han2004}. For these reasons, it was hypothesized that the AS bias of RTs in genes was due to a selective process.   

To distinguish whether AS bias was truly a result of selection over time or if it was due to integration, the distribution of relatively recent Alu insertions were examined, as well as the change in AS bias over evolutionary time. 
    
%1000 genomes by population and Faulkner data
%ASbias upon insertion
\section{Retrotransposon Antisense Bias and the Process of Integration}

Under the hypothesis that selection is the driving force of AS bias in genes, the difference in AS and S elements should accumulate over time, and newly inserted RTs should have no observable bias. Relatively young Alu and L1 were therefore studied to examine the AS bias of newly inserted elements. Three groups of young RTs (Alu and L1) were used for this analysis. Groups \textit{a} and \textit{b} were filtered groups of Alu and L1 that were annotated as insertions in the \num{1000} genomes project \cite{Stewart2011}. Group \textit{c} Alu and L1 were annotated as newly identified germline insertions \cite{Baillie2011, Bundo2013}. All three groups represented RTs that were polymorphic with relatively small residence times in the population (young). Here, polymorphic refers to the status of presence or absence of the entire element where any mutations within the element were irrelevant to the status.

\subsection{Allele Frequencies of Polymorphic Alu Used in This Analysis}
\label{sec:af}
Since the goal was to determine if either the immediate force of integration or the longitudinal force of selection was responsible for AS bias, elements were grouped based on residence of time in the population. Population allele frequency was used as a proxy for residence time. Alu in groups \textit{a} and \textit{b} were initially identified in the 1000 genomes project as being polymorphic between individuals \cite{Stewart2011}. The allele frequencies of these elements were calculated from three populations; Yoruban (YRI); European (CEU); and Chinese/Japanese (CHBJPT) \cite{Stewart2011}. For the current analysis, 1000 genomes annoted Alu were separated into the two groups mentioned above: \textit{a}) population-specific Alu (i.e.: Allele Frequency (AF) > 0 in only one population), and \textit{b}) Alu present among all three populations. The expecatation was that elements present in only one population were more likley to have small residence times (\textit{a}). Similarly elements present prior to the split of the three populations would be present in all three populations and would likely have longer residence times (\textit{b}). The mean AFs of group \textit{a} Alu were 0.091 ($\pm$0.071), 0.067 ($\pm$0.047), and 0.070 ($\pm$0.067) in YRI, CEU, and CHBJPT respectively. To identify the mean AF of group \textit{b} Alu, the maximum population-specific AF was identified per element. The average of these maximum AFs was significantly higher than the population-specific sets 0.279 ($\pm$0.16) (Wilcoxon rank sum p$_{, YRI}$ < 1.3e-184; p$_{, CEU}$ < 2.6e-62; p$_{, CHBJPT}$ < 8.5e-49). The AFs of group \textit{c} Alu were similar in all three populations (figure \ref{fig:AF_3d}). Since AFs are correlated with residence times in the population \cite{Li1975}, these AFs indicate that group \textit{a} Alu have shorter residence times (younger) than group \textit{b}.

    %Figure 
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{AF_3d.png}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Similar AFs of shared Alu\\} Correlations of  Allele Frequencies (AF) bettween CEU (European), YRI (Yoruban), and Chinese/Japanese (CHBJPT) populations.}}
        \label{fig:AF_3d}
    \end{figure}

\subsection{Young AS and S Alu are Present in Equal Proportions}
\label{sec:youngas}
Although the allele frequencies of group \textit{c} RTs were unknown, they were identified in Baillie et. al. as being present in the germline insertions. Since group \textit{a} and \textit{c} RTs all represent young polymorphic insertions the counts were combined across all groups to reduce type II error by increasing sample size (table \ref{table:youngasbias}). The probability of choosing an AS RT in this combined group was tested versus an expected probability of 0.50 using the binomial sign test. The hypothesis that young insertions had an AS bias equal to 0.50 could not be rejected (p(AS) = 0.50 ; \num{95}\% CI = 0.47 -- 0.53; p = 0.84). It was noted, that there may have been a bias imparted to the calculation by combining both group \text{a} and \textit{c} RTs. Group \textit{a} RTs were therefore tested separately, despite a reduction in power, and also  did not have a p(AS) significantly different from 0.5 (p(AS) = 0.53; \num{95}\% CI = 0.48 -- 0.57; p = 0.20). Although the results of insignificance indicated that young RTs may not have an AS bias, the null hypothesis can not be proved, only rejected \cite{Popper1959,Wilckinson2013}. Therefore, young RTs were tested against the AS bias of the reference RTs, to determine if the AS bias of young elements was significantly different from the bias that is often cited in the literature \cite{Zhang2011}. 


