    %\end{figure}
    
\subsection{The Ages of Alu and L1 are Dependent on the Chromosome of Origin}

The above results indicated that both Alu and L1 were undergoing selection within genes, though at different levels. To further test whether purifying selection or positive selection was acting on these RTs within genes, I took advantage of the differing rates of selection on chrX, chrY, and the autosomes. It's been shown previously that the ability for purifying selection of minorly deleterious alleles [??TRUE?] is reduced on chrY compared to chrX and the autosomes. Furthermore, there are varied effective population sizes between chrX, chrY, and the autosomes (section \ref{sec:selection}). Therefore, if selection is indeed acting on RTs within genes, elements should have different ages depending on the chromosome on which they reside. For this reason, and for the overall lack of purifying selection on chrY it was hypothesized that the age of RTs would be the lowest on chrX and the autosomes, while chrY would be expected to have older elements due to the lack of purifying selection.

To have a broad idea of the age of RTs across chromosomes, each placement group was analyzed with all subfamilies aggregated together. Although aggregating all subfamilies into a single measure was expected to wash out much of the signal, there were significant differences between chromosomes when analyzed this way (table \ref{table:chrxyage}). 

