%Signs of purifying and positive selection
\subsection{Evidence of Purifying and Postive Selection on S and AS L1}

         %Figure 
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{hclust_l1_chr.pdf}
        \caption{\textbf{Clustering of L1 by Age\\} Red: Sense; Green: Antisense; Black: Intergenic}
        \label{fig:hclustl1chr}
    \end{figure}

L1 elements in autosomes were clustered in one major branch and L1 elements on chrX were clustered on a second major branch (figure \ref{fig:hclustl1chr}). Interestingly, L1 on chrY were interspersed within chrX and autosomes. When compared to using Student's t-tests S L1 on chrY were significantly younger than AS L1 on chrY (table \ref{table:l1chrsig}), indicating a potential difference in selective force acting on S and AS L1 on chrY. Moreover, AS L1 on chrY were older on average than intergenic L1 on chrY. These effects are mimicked by the antisense ratios (table \ref{table:l1asbiaschr}), further implicating selection in the derivation of the altered distribution of RTs within genes. 

